ce:section.ce:para:
For preliminary evaluation of 0.05B-CDs@MgO detection ability towards ethyl-paraoxon with different concentrations, the fluorescent spectra were firstly determined in deionized water (Fig. 6
                        ). The fluorescence intensity showed concentration dependence of ethyl-paraoxon, and the emission peak position was redshifted with the increasing concentrations of ethyl-paraoxon (0–100 μg/mL, Fig. 6A). The reason was that the p-NP could reduce the fluorescence intensity of B-CDs by IFE [32]. The Abs. of p-NP shows a sufficient overlap region with the Ex. and Em. of B-CDs in the 300–500 nm range (Fig. S10A), indicating an IFE-based sensing system. In order to further confirm IFE, the fluorescence lifetimes of 0.05B-CDs@MgO in the presence of different concentrations of ethyl-paraoxon were conducted. As shown in Figs. S10B and S10C, the fluorescence lifetime of 0.05B-CDs@MgO remains unchanged compared to the blank control since the fluorescence quenching induced by IFE did not impact the excited state of 0.05B-CDs@MgO. The benzene ring structures might cause the emission redshift of 0.05B-CDs@MgO peaks by inherently reducing energy gaps of B-CDs through larger sp2 domains (Fig. S11) [66]. Meanwhile, the ethyl-paraoxon itself could also reduce the fluorescence intensity of CDs [31]. The fluorescent photos under UV 365 nm in Fig. 6B inset showed the trend with the fluorescence intensity gradually decreasing, and the visual color was changed from cyan-blue to yellow-green. It was found that fluorescence intensity ratio (F0/F) vs. ethyl-paraoxon concentration was well fitted as two-stage segment linearization between 0–10 μg/mL and 10–100 μg/mL (Fig. 6B, C, and 6D). And the linear equations were y = 0.025x+0.99 (n = 3, R2 = 0.99) and y = 0.0093x+1.11 (n = 3, R2 = 0.99), respectively. Such a phenomenon confirmed the hypothesis and prompted us to explore the situation for detecting ethyl-paraoxon in actual river water (Fig. 7
                        ).
